<body>
    <h1>Extruder PID Controller Setup in Python</h1>
    <p><strong>Author: Ihor Kryazhev, Process Consultant</strong></p>
    <h2>1. The Problem of Dead Time</h2>
    <p>Extruders suffer from transport delay. A standard P-controller causes oscillations; a PID controller with proper <strong>Kd</strong> (Derivative) action is required to handle sudden changes in material bulk density (agglomerate).</p>
    <h2>2. Sampling Time (dt)</h2>
    <p>The optimal sampling period <strong>dt</strong> for an extruder is <strong>2–5 seconds</strong>. If dt < 2s, the controller reacts to sensor noise. If dt > 10s, it fails to correct output drops in time.</p>
    <h2>3. Implementation</h2>
    <pre>class PID:
    def compute(self, measured):
        error = self.setpoint - measured
        self._integral += error * self.dt
        # Anti-windup logic here
        derivative = (error - self._prev_error) / self.dt
        return Kp*error + Ki*self._integral + Kd*derivative</pre>
</body>
